This data is NOT tidy. Why is it not tidy?

Each row has multiple datapoints or observations.

It is “easy” to see the trend in this data… just following a row. However, each row does not refer to a specific, unique thing.

So… what data is tidy?

# install.packages("babynames")
library(babynames)
data("babynames")
babynames

Each row is a name, year, gender, and then n number of people who were born and named that. This is “tidy.”

Why is it tidy, again? For one, we can easily figure out the top names.

babynames %>% 
    group_by(sex, name) %>% 
    summarise(total_births = sum(n)) %>% 
    arrange(desc(total_births))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'sex'. You can override using the `.groups`

We could do this by year, too…

babynames %>%

    arrange(desc(total_births))

babynames %>%

Reshaping Data

All is not lost, though, if our data is not tidy.

In comes pivot_wider and pivot_longer to help us go to and from tidy format.

PS - earlier I taught reshape2 to some of you. That is a valid option, too, but not what the book teaches. Whatever works, works.

Wide to long

hiv_long <- hiv %>% 
    select(`Estimated HIV Prevalence% - (Ages 15-49)`:`2008`) %>%
    pivot_longer(-`Estimated HIV Prevalence% - (Ages 15-49)`, 
                 names_to = "year", 
                 values_to = "percent") %>% 
    na.omit() %>% 
    mutate(year = as.numeric(year),
           percent = percent / 100)
hiv_long
## # A tibble: 2,863 × 3
##    `Estimated HIV Prevalence% - (Ages 15-49)`  year percent

Before we made this change, we couldn’t plot the data. Now we can!

ggplot(hiv_long, aes(x = year, y = percent, 
                     group = `Estimated HIV Prevalence% - (Ages 15-49)`,
                     color = `Estimated HIV Prevalence% - (Ages 15-49)`)) + 
    geom_line() + 
    theme(legend.position = "none")

Pivot Wider

We can also go the other way, for any number of reasons. Let’s say we are working with a colleague who relies on Excel? They will need the data in wide format to graph it or use it.

baby_wide <- babynames %>% 
    filter(name %in% c("Jacob", "Lucas", "Elizabeth", "Regina", "Sasha", "Poppy")) %>% 
    select(year:n) %>% 
    pivot_wider(names_from = year, values_from = n)
baby_wide
